g.text: YELLOW-LEGGED FROG
Outdoor recreation and fishing are important traditions for
many families in the US and a core value across national parks.
Over time, our policies adjusted to reflect these societal values
at the detriment of the frog.
95% of the population vanished
leaving only 5% to survive
The Sierra Nevada Yellow-Legged Frog was one of the most
common amphibians found in the high-elevation aquatic systems
of the Sierra Nevada. People would watch their step as they
navigated around hundreds of frogs hopping around a lake.
But today, there are only a few lakes where you can find them.
Chytrid fungus runs rampant among
frogs, attacking their skin. Frogs skin is
not only their outer layer, but also their
respiratory and excretory systems
Policies that priotize human
interests, including fishing
and recreational activites
Chytriad fungus is the cause of Chytridiomycosis, an infec
tious disease that affects amphibians worldwide. The equiv
alent effect of the disease on humans would be a disease
that single-handedly destroyed the lungs, kidneys, and skin
all at once!

text.tspan: keystone species in the wetland ecosystem

g.text: The Yellow-Legged Frog plays a vital role in the food chain, serving as
predators of insects and prey for native birds, snakes, and mammals.
While its too late to protect them from the chytrid fungus, experimen
tal habitat restoration efforts in Yosemite are allowing the frogs to
make a comeback.
